  aes(log2FoldChange, -log(padj)) +
  geom_point()

(`geom_point()`).
mycols <- rep("gray", nrow(res))
mycols[ abs(res$log2FoldChange) > 2 ] <- "red"
inds <- (res$padj < 0.01) & (abs(res$log2FoldChange) > 2)
mycols[inds] <- "blue"

plot(res$log2FoldChange, -log(res$padj), col=mycols, 
     xlab="Log2(FoldChange)", ylab="-Log(P-value)")

abline(h=-log(0.01), col="gray", lty=2)

Reactome

Lots of people like the reactome web interface. You can also run this as an R function but lets look at the website first < https://reactome.org/ >

The website wants a text file with one gene symbol per line of the genes you want to map to pathways

sig_genes <- res[res$padj <= 0.05 & !is.na(res$padj), "symbol"]
head(sig_genes)
ENSG00000187634 ENSG00000188976 ENSG00000187961 ENSG00000188290 ENSG00000187608 
       "SAMD11"         "NOC2L"        "KLHL17"          "HES4"         "ISG15" 
ENSG00000188157 
         "AGRN"

and write out a file:

write.table(sig_genes, file="significant_genes.txt", row.names=FALSE, col.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)

Save our results

write.csv(res, file = "myresults.csv")
